{"id":9612,"date":"2020-02-03T20:05:04","date_gmt":"2020-02-03T20:05:04","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/new.defyhatenow.org\/?page_id=9612"},"modified":"2020-11-18T16:04:52","modified_gmt":"2020-11-18T16:04:52","slug":"defyhatenow_cameroon","status":"publish","type":"page","link":"https:\/\/defyhatenow.org\/defyhatenow_cameroon\/","title":{"rendered":"#defyhatenow_Cameroon"},"content":{"rendered":"<div id='av_section_1'  class='avia-section main_color avia-section-default avia-no-border-styling  avia-bg-style-scroll  avia-builder-el-0  el_before_av_section  avia-builder-el-first   container_wrap sidebar_right' style=' '  ><div class='container' ><main  role=\"main\" itemprop=\"mainContentOfPage\"  class='template-page content  av-content-small alpha units'><div class='post-entry post-entry-type-page post-entry-9612'><div class='entry-content-wrapper clearfix'>\n<div  style='padding-bottom:10px; ' class='av-special-heading av-special-heading-h2  blockquote modern-quote modern-centered  avia-builder-el-1  el_before_av_three_fifth  avia-builder-el-first  '><h2 class='av-special-heading-tag '  itemprop=\"headline\"  >#defyhatenow Cameroon<\/h2><div class='special-heading-border'><div class='special-heading-inner-border' ><\/div><\/div><\/div>\n<div class='flex_column_table av-equal-height-column-flextable -flextable' ><div class=\"flex_column av_three_fifth  flex_column_table_cell av-equal-height-column av-align-middle av-zero-column-padding first  avia-builder-el-2  el_after_av_heading  el_before_av_two_fifth  \" style='border-radius:0px; '><section class=\"av_textblock_section \"  itemscope=\"itemscope\" itemtype=\"https:\/\/schema.org\/CreativeWork\" ><div class='avia_textblock  '   itemprop=\"text\" ><h3 id=\"mobilising-civic-action-to-counter-hate-speech-and-violent-extremism-both-online-and-offline\" class=\"part\" data-startline=\"1\" data-endline=\"1\">Mobilising Civic Action to Counter Hate Speech and Violent Extremism both Online and Offline<\/h3>\n<p class=\"part\" align=\"justify\" data-startline=\"3\" data-endline=\"3\"><strong>#defyhatenow Cameroon<\/strong> exists to strengthen the voices and support the actions of primarily youth, community and media oriented civil society organizations to counter social media based hate speech, conflict rhetoric and directed online incitement to violence in response to <strong>Cameroon\u2019s \u2018Anglophone Crisis\u2019<\/strong>. The project provides capacity building and media literacy trainings to enable community based organizations and citizens, including people displaced by conflict, to become positive influencers with counter-actions, fact-checking and early response monitoring skills, peacebuilding, as well as education and culture oriented activities in a rapidly evolving social media landscape, rather than leaving that space open to agents of conflict.<\/p>\n<p class=\"part\" align=\"justify\" data-startline=\"5\" data-endline=\"5\">Online hate speech, propaganda, incitement to violence, and threats are posted and shared by numerous users and agents, from within the country and through the international diaspora &#8211; both knowingly and unaware of the consequences of their messaging. Many are organised, acting as conflict influencers in social media groups and on time-lines. They target fellow citizens, community organisations, schools, governments, international agencies &#8211; cutting across all social strata, both Anglophone and Francophone.<\/p>\n<p class=\"part\" align=\"justify\" data-startline=\"7\" data-endline=\"7\">In April 2019, <a href=\"https:\/\/openculture.agency\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><strong>r0g_agency for open culture &amp; critical transformation gGmbH<\/strong><\/a> in partnership with the <strong>UNESCO Multisectoral Regional Office for Central Africa<\/strong> in Yaound\u00e9, and since September 2019 with the support of the German Federal Foreign Office, #defyhatenow has been mandated to address the use of social media in the country\u2019s crisis. In-country and international #defyhatenow teams and conflict mitigation specialists are thus acting to address the resultant civil conflicts and destabilization issues including violent extremism, internal displacement and refugee movements, including the use of the <strong>Covid-19 pandemic<\/strong> to exacerbate the conflict through targeted disinformation. The initiative is engaging a broad spectrum of civil society actors in creating a peacebuilding framework, by also bridging gaps of knowledge and awareness of social media mechanisms between those with access to technology and those without.<\/p>\n<p class=\"part\" align=\"justify\" data-startline=\"9\" data-endline=\"9\">Through the grant provided by the <a href=\"http:\/\/www.auswaertiges-amt.de\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><strong>German Federal Foreign Office<\/strong><\/a>, this peacebuilding collaboration has been enabled to keep the many conflict mitigation conversations going, develop public resources, including a comprehensive bilingual Social Media Hate Speech Mitigation Field Guide and to support local activist and peace oriented media-based activities.<\/p>\n<\/div><\/section><\/div><div class='av-flex-placeholder'><\/div><div class=\"flex_column av_two_fifth  flex_column_table_cell av-equal-height-column av-align-middle av-zero-column-padding   avia-builder-el-4  el_after_av_three_fifth  avia-builder-el-last  \" style='border-radius:0px; '><p><div   data-size='no scaling'  data-lightbox_size='large'  data-animation='fade'  data-conditional_play=''  data-ids='13483,13484'  data-video_counter='0'  data-autoplay='true'  data-bg_slider='false'  data-slide_height=''  data-handle='av_slideshow'  data-interval='3'  data-class=' avia-builder-el-5  el_before_av_slideshow  avia-builder-el-first  '  data-el_id=''  data-css_id=''  data-scroll_down=''  data-control_layout='av-control-minimal av-control-minimal-dark'  data-custom_markup=''  data-perma_caption=''  